  Command Continuation,"
      Command Continuation       

To facilitate editing and viewing of a long command in the Command window, you may want to continue the command on additional line(s).  To continue a command on additional lines, place a semicolon between keywords or clauses then press Enter and type the remainder of the command on the next line.  Note that lines in programs may also be split in the same manner.

When a command is continued on multiple lines and you want to use && and include comments with the command, the comments cannot be placed after a semicolon.  Instead, they must appear on the last line of the command.

Following is an example of a long SELECT command properly broken onto multiple lines:

SELECT customer.cust_id, ;
		customer.contact, ;
		customer.city, ;
		customer.state, ;
		customer.zip ;
	FROM customer ;
	ORDER BY customer.state, ;
		customer.zip
		
When you are ready to execute a command split onto multiple lines, place the cursor on any line of the command and press Enter.  To insert a new line into a split command, press Ctrl+Enter.

Indentation greatly improves the readability of commands split onto multiple lines in the Command window.  To indent a command in the Command window, press Tab before typing the command.  You may press Tab repeatedly for additional indentation.  Once a line is indented in the Command window, following lines may be automatically indented the same amount by pressing Ctrl+Enter to move the cursor to the next line. 

The maximum number of characters per command line is 2,048.  If macro substitution is used, the maximum number of characters in any single macro is 255 (after the macro is expanded).  Multiple macro substitutions can be combined on one command line, up to a maximum of 2,048 characters.",General wi
  Commonly Asked Questions,"
         Common Questions        

RQBE (Relational Query By Example)
	-	The query window is by definition a ""read only"" window which displays the SELECT command being created through RQBE.  If you must edit the query directly rather than using RQBE, simply copy and paste the query into a program editing window.

	-	Cursors reside on the SORTWORK drive.

Screen Builder
	-	If you'd like to call a generated .SPR program as a UDF, for example, X = FRED(), specify the generated program name as FRED.PRG in the Save As dialog.

	-	If you are developing utility screen panels, use the M. prefix for variables to avoid conflicts with a database field with that name.

	-	If you create a borderless window in the Screen Builder by choosing the NONE option, the window's size cannot be changed with the mouse.  However, you can change the size of the window with the keyboard.  This is also true when the actual window is active. 
	
	-	#SECTION 1 | 2 generator directives allow you to split the setup code for a screen into two sections.  Setup Code -- Section 1 is generated at the beginning of the .SPR program.  Setup Code -- Section 2 is generated after the DEFINE WINDOW commands and before the Screen Layout commands.  You would split the setup code if you wanted to include a PARAMETER statement or an ON ERROR statement in the screen program.

		*****  #SECTION 1 | 2 *****
		Precede commands to be inserted in section one of setup code with a #SECTION 1.  If you would like other setup code placed in Setup Code - Section 2, a #SECTION 2 generator directive should follow commands in section 1.

			#SECTION 1 
			PARAMETER x, y, z
				<other commands>
			#SECTION 2
				<other commands>

Report Writer
	-	The text box at the bottom of the Group Info dialog allows you to specify the number of rows that will follow the group header.  If the number of blank rows at the bottom of the page (excluding the page footer) is less than the number specified with this option, the header is forced to the top of the next page.  Use this feature to prevent your headers from being orphaned -- standing alone at the bottom of a page and separated from information on the next page.

		For example, if you would like at least five lines of detail information to follow a group header, you would enter 5 in the text box.  When you run the report, if there are less than five lines remaining on a page when the group header is to be printed, the group header is forced to the next page.

		This feature will work for any report object and is especially handy for variable length fields such as memo fields.

	-	Specifying a format in the Report Expression dialog does not change the field size.  If you want to change the size of the field, you must type the desired width in the Width text box of the Report Expression dialog.

	-	If the calculations in your report are not working as you expected, check the order of your variables in the Report Variable dialog.  Variables are evaluated in the order they appear in the list.  Any variable issued as part of an expression in another variable must precede that variable in the list in the Report Variables dialog.

		Also check the initial value setting for each variable and the point where the variable will be reset to its initial value.

	-	A Suppress Blank Lines check box has been added to the Page Layout Options dialog.

		When the Suppress Blank Lines option is checked, lines in the Detail band of a report that contain only blank fields are removed from the report.  If the report line contains other fields or text (in addition to the blank field), the line is not suppressed.

		A field must be blank to be affected by this option.  For example, if a numeric field contains no data, its value is 0 (zero).  It is not a blank field.  You can, however, check the Blank if Zero check box in the Format dialog to make numeric fields that contain 0 (zero) blank fields.  (This places an @Z in the Format text box in the Report Expression dialog.)  The report line containing the field will then be removed.

		Suppress Blank Lines does not remove lines with no objects from the Detail band.  For example, if the Detail band in your report is defined to be five lines deep and only three of the lines contain objects, the report prints five lines for the Detail band.  You can manually remove empty lines from a report with the Remove Line option on the Report menu popup, or by dragging the Detail band until it is the desired size.

Macros
	-	If the macro you have created processes faster than you anticipated, put in pauses in the appropriate places.

Indexes
	-	FoxPro lets you create two types of index files:

			Compound .CDX index files containing multiple index entries called tags

			.IDX index files containing one index entry

		A structural compound index file can be created that will automatically be opened with the database file.  Because structural .CDX index files are automatically opened when the database is opened, they are the preferred index type.

		Include the COMPACT clause with the INDEX ON command to create compact .IDX index files.  .CDX index files are always compact.

		If you are sharing files between FoxPro and FoxBASE+ or FoxBASE+/Mac, you must use non-compact .IDX index files.  Otherwise, if you build .IDX files always include COMPACT to benefit from FoxPro 2.0's faster access index technology.

	-	Adding tags to .CDX files through INDEX ON can quickly result in very large indexes.  To reduce the size of the indexes, REINDEX as part of your maintenance.

	-	After an unsuccessful SEEK in an indexed database, RECNO(0) uses ""soft seek"" logic to determine the record number to return.  If the SEEK is unsuccessful and no matching record is found, RECNO(0) returns the record number of the next closest match.  If a close match cannot be found, RECNO(0) returns 0.

		If the seek value is greater than the last record in the database, the message ""Record out of range"" is issued for the GO RECNO(0) command.

	-	It may take longer than you expect to add many records to a database that has an index with many tags.  To make the process quicker:

		1.	Delete the .CDX file.
			
		2.	Append the records.
			
		3.	Rebuild the .CDX file.
 
Trace
	-	You can pass parameters to a program or an application and then trace execution by following these steps:

		1.	Open the Trace window.

		2.	From the Program menu in the Trace window, choose Open... and choose the program or application.

		3.	Set a breakpoint on the first executable line of the program.

		4.	In the Command window, DO the program WITH the parameters.

Colors
	-	Place text behind invisible buttons to produce the enabled/disabled invisible button color effect.

SELECT - SQL
	-	Subqueries can only appear on the right hand side of a =, <>, <, >, <=, >=, !=, SOME | ANY | ALL, [NOT] IN, or [NOT] EXISTS.  This can interfere with the natural expression of a problem.  For example, suppose you want to list the salespersons whose sales exceed the average by 10%.  The following is a more natural, but syntactically incorrect query:

			SELECT;
				SALESMAN, NAME;
			FROM;
				SALESMAN;
			WHERE;
				YTDSALES > 1.10 * (SELECT AVG(YTDSALES) FROM SALESMAN)
		
		Instead you must phrase the query as:
		
			SELECT;
				SALESMAN, NAME;
			FROM;
				SALESMAN;
			WHERE;
				YTDSALES/1.10 > (SELECT AVG(YTDSALES) FROM SALESMAN)
				
	-	If a query is taking longer than expected, check that you have included all the join conditions intended.  When two tables are joined without a join condition, the result is a table with a record count equal to the product of the record counts of the two original tables.  This is rarely what is intended.

		For example, suppose you start with the following query:
		
			SELECT;
				COMPANY, ITOTAL;
			FROM;
				CUSTOMER, INVOICES;
			WHERE;
				CUSTOMER.CNO = INVOICES.CNO
		
		This produces a record for each invoice, listing the company and the invoice total.  Suppose you decide that you also want to know the salesperson for each of the invoices.  You then modify the above query as follows:

			SELECT;
				COMPANY, NAME, ITOTAL;
			FROM;
				CUSTOMER, INVOICES, SALESMAN;
			WHERE;
				CUSTOMER.CNO = INVOICES.CNO
		
		Having forgotten the join condition ""SALESMAN.SALESMAN = INVOICES.SALESMAN"", this produces an output record for every combination of invoices and salesman.  Not only is this not the intention, but it will take much longer to execute.

	-	When formulating queries it is helpful to have a diagram of your database tables showing the link fields, such as the diagrams in the SQL Quiz chapter of the Developer's Guide and Session 6 of Getting Started.

	-	Name expressions can only be substituted for macros where the command is expecting a single variable name or file name.  The following examples show correct and incorrect syntax.

			*	Correct
			filename = 'salesman.dbf'
			SELECT n FROM (filename).
			
			*	Incorrect.  This syntax cannot be used because the SELECT statement can expect a list of fields to select.
			field = 'salesman'
			SELECT (field) FROM salesman
			
	-	Functions such as BOF(), DBF(), DELETED(), EOF(), FIELD(), FOUND(), RECCOUNT(), RECNO(), etc., will work in single tables as long as you do not specify an alias.  These functions, however, will produce unpredictable results in multiple tables.

	-	ORDER BY is similar to an index in that it orders the file by the field or function specified.  It does not create a special file like an index.  GROUP BY produces a summary of the records you are grouping.  This is different from data grouping in the Report Writer in that the Report Writer does not produce summary records but rather acts as a division line between groups of records.

	-	Cursors reside on the SORTWORK drive.
	
Miscellaneous

	-	If you open a .VUE file and it cannot find all the necessary files to open, all the files that can be found are opened, and an error message IS NOT generated.",General er
  Compatibility,"
          Compatibility          

Compatibility with FoxBASE+ and other languages is controlled by the SET COMPATIBLE command.

SET COMPATIBLE FOXPLUS
	In this mode (the default), programs written in FoxBASE+ (and DB3) run without change.  SET COMPATIBLE FOXPLUS may be used interchangeably with SET COMPATIBLE OFF.  Try to run with SET COMPATIBLE FOXPLUS.  New applications should always be written in FOXPLUS mode.

SET COMPATIBLE DB4
	In this mode, most programs written in DB4 run without change.  SET COMPATIBLE DB4 may be used interchangeably with SET COMPATIBLE ON.  In DB4 compatible mode, FoxPro is forced to emulate an environment that basically does NOT support real windowing.  This leads to some unfortunate irregularities arising out of the need for compatibility.


	Commands/Functions Affected
		by SET COMPATIBLE 

Certain file processing commands
ACTIVATE SCREEN
ACTIVATE WINDOW
APPEND MEMO
MENU and POPUP commands
PLAY MACRO
READ with a VALID clause
SET COLOR TO
SET FIELDS
SET MESSAGE
STORE 
SUM
INKEY()
LASTKEY()
LIKE()
SELECT()
SYS(2001, ""COLOR"")


     FoxBASE+ Compatibility      

FoxPro WILL run FoxBASE+ programs without change, but you must inform FoxPro whether you desire FoxBASE+ or dBASE IV compatibility.  If you

	SET COMPATIBLE FOXPLUS
	
(the default), most programs written in FoxBASE+ and DB3 run without change.

FoxPro recognizes the following FoxBASE+ file types:

	-	Source programs (.PRGs) - These are automatically compiled to FoxPro compatible object programs (.FXPs).  See the section that follows about .FOX program files.

	-	Database files (.DBFs)

	-	Memo files (.DBTs) - While FoxPro recognizes .DBT-style memo files, it only converts them to FoxPro compatible memo files, with an extension of .FPT, when a new file is created from the old structure.  FoxPro can read and write to .DBT memo files without converting them to the new format, and it does not automatically replace the original .DBT files.

	-	Index files (.IDXs) - See the section that follows about .NDX files.

	-	Memory variable save files (.MEM files)

	-	Screen format files (.FMT files) - FoxPro automatically compiles .FMT files into .PRX files whenever you execute the SET FORMAT TO command.

	-	Report form files (.FRM files) - While the FoxPro Report Writer creates report form files in a different format than the FoxBASE+ format, FoxPro can print reports using the old .FRM format.  The Report Writer can also read .FRM type reports for modification, although it cannot save report files in the old .FRM format.

	-	Label definition files (.LBL files).

	The file types listed above require no modification before using them with FoxPro -- FoxPro handles all file conversion for you.

	-	.NDX Index Files

		As in previous Fox products, the indexes used to access FoxPro databases are different in format and usually much smaller than comparable dbase indexes.  This is due to the state-of-the-art indexing technique used by FoxPro.

		If you're running applications that contain dbase .NDX index files, you don't have to worry about converting your index files to FoxPro format -- we take care of it for you!

		When you run a dbase application under FoxPro and use a dbase-style index file, FoxPro immediately and automatically reindexes the database, creating a FoxPro index file.  The following message appears:

			dBASE III index - rebuilding

		By default, these new index files are created with an extension of IDX.  Some applications, however, may be written to require that index files have an .NDX extension.  If that's the case, add the following line to the CONFIG.FP file:

			INDEX = NDX

		This causes FoxPro to use the .NDX extension with all index files it creates.  Of course, using this option will cause the original dBASE indexes to be destroyed during the automatic reindexing process.

	-	.DBT Memo Files

		FoxPro memo files (.FPTs) are slightly different than those used by FoxBASE+, dBASE III PLUS and dBASE IV (.DBTs) in that you can store any type of data in them.  The old style .DBT files only hold ASCII text data.  FoxPro, however, can read and write to .DBT memo files without converting them to the new format.

		FoxPro creates a new .FPT type memo file from an existing .DBT file in two situations:

		-	Whenever you create a new database structure from an existing database that contains a memo field and has an existing memo file.  The COPY TO command is an example.

		-	Whenever you modify the structure of a database that has an associated memo file.  When the structure changes are saved, the .DBT file is converted to a new .FPT file.

		To create a copy of a FoxPro database file that contains a memo field in the form that FoxBASE+ can understand, issue the following command:

			COPY TO <filename> TYPE FOXPLUS

		You should do this when your memo fields contain only characters which can be processed by FoxBASE+.  The forbidden characters, such as Ctrl+Z (CHR(26)) and Null (CHR(0)), should not be included. 

	-	FOX Program Files

		FoxPro handles program compilation and management somewhat differently than in previous versions.

		If you have existing FoxBASE+ programs that you'd like to execute, take note that FoxPro does not recognize or execute .FOX compiled programs.  Existing source files need to be compiled into .FXPs before they can be executed.  FoxPro automatically compiles any source .PRG file for which it cannot find a compiled  .FXP object file with the same name.  You can also use one of the manual compile options.

A few other details, as described next, must be handled to insure complete FoxBASE+ compatibility.

FOXPLUS.FP
	To make it as simple as possible, we've provided a special CONFIG file that configures FoxPro to be completely FoxBASE+ compatible.  It's in the GOODIES directory and is called FOXPLUS.FP.  Simply rename it to be CONFIG.FP or incorporate its contents into your own CONFIG.FP.

Emulating FoxBASE+ Keystroke Assignments
	FoxPro's default keystrokes are very similar to those of FoxBASE+/Mac and are also similar to those of IBM's SAA (System Application Architecture) specification.

	Therefore, if your programs rely on the exact keystrokes used to operate FoxBASE+ (and the READKEY() codes they generate), you will also need to utilize FOXPLUS.FKY, a special set of keyboard macros which reproduce FoxBASE+ keystrokes.

	These macros are activated by the command: RESTORE MACROS FROM FOXPLUS.FKY


	SET Options Required for
	Complete FoxBASE+ Emulation

		SET BRSTATUS ON
		SET HEADING OFF
		SET MACKEY TO
		SET NOTIFY OFF
		SET SCOREBOARD ON
		SET STATUS ON
	
Some of the above settings, while required for complete compatibility, are not really desirable in the context of FoxPro.  A good example is SET STATUS ON, which activates the old-style status bar.  This is not really useful in native FoxPro mode -- it's just for backward compatibility.

Recompile Your Programs
	Programs written in FoxBASE+ must be recompiled in FoxPro.  FoxPro will automatically compile a FoxBASE+ program when it is first run, but you may also want to compile your FoxBASE+ programs before running them in FoxPro.
 
Incompatibilities
	Certain FoxBASE+ features behave differently or cannot be supported in FoxPro.  Here is a list of known incompatibilities:

	1.	 Arrays or user-defined functions created in FoxBASE+ may have been assigned the same names as new FoxPro functions.  These arrays or user-defined functions must be given new names.

	2.	The SET DEFAULT command performs a full DOS CHDIR (change directory) command in FoxPro.  FoxBASE+ does not perform a full DOS CHDIR command.  In FoxBASE+ you may only specify a DEFAULT drive; you may not include a directory specification as in FoxPro.

	3.	FoxPro .VUE files save the index order of the database.  In FoxBASE+ the index order is not saved.

	4.	FoxPro detects a few error conditions that FoxBASE+ ignores.  If your FoxBASE+ programs contain these errors, they will not run under FoxPro as they do under FoxBASE+, but instead will generate error messages.

	5.	Any program statements that have been written to rely on the fact that null characters cannot be placed in a string will not operate under FoxPro as under FoxBASE+.  For example, if a FoxBASE+ program initializes a string to the null string (containing no characters) with the command

		mystring = CHR(0)

		as opposed to the FoxPro technique of

		mystring = """"

		the program won't work under FoxPro as it did in FoxBASE+.  In the first case FoxPro (which permits the null character to be stored in strings) would create a string that contains one character, the null character.

	6.	Because FoxPro's interface and interactive facilities (like BROWSE, CHANGE and EDIT) look entirely different from those of FoxBASE+, programs that rely on the precise physical appearance of the facilities in FoxBASE+ will not operate identically in FoxPro.

	7.	Issuing the command SET COLOR TO in FoxBASE+ will reset the screen to the default colors of black and white.  Issuing the same command in FoxPro has no effect.

	8.	In commands that let you specify a color pair or pairs, including the ""color"" U in a color pair causes underlining on monochrome monitors.  On a color monitor FoxBASE+ ignores the color U in a color pair and uses the color black in its place.  On a color monitor in FoxPro:

			If you specify U anywhere in a color pair the foreground will be blue.

			If you specify a background color of U or you don't specify a background color, the background will be black.

			If you specify a background color other than U, you will get the expected color.

		Specifying the ""color"" I causes inverse video on monochrome monitors.  On a color monitor FoxBASE+ ignores the color I in a color pair and uses the color black in its place.  With FoxPro and a color monitor, specifying I as the background or foreground color in a color pair gives a black foreground and a white background.

	9.	A FILES statement in the FoxPro CONFIG.FP configuration file will be ignored.

	10.	In FoxBASE+ you can use the COPY FILE command to make copies of a file that is open.  In FoxPro the file must be closed before it can be copied with COPY FILE.

	11.	FoxPro inserts a formfeed, the path and name of the file and the date at the beginning of output from the TYPE command when HEADING is SET ON.  FoxBASE+ does not insert this extra information, nor does FoxPro if HEADING is SET OFF.


        DB3 Compatibility        

FoxPro WILL run DB3 programs unchanged.  See the Help discussion on FoxBASE+ compatibility for details.


        DB4 Compatibility        

FoxPro will run MOST DB4 programs unchanged.
        
If you

	SET COMPATIBLE DB4
	
most programs written in DB4 will run without change.

You can also use or adapt the FOXPLUS.FKY keyboard macros if your applications are dependent on the exact keystroke assignments of DB4 (which are different than DB3).",General cm
  Configuring FoxPro,"
       Configuring FoxPro        

When you install FoxPro, it's configured to work the way most users prefer.  Many of FoxPro's settings can be adjusted for your particular hardware configuration, your personal taste or to improve performance.  Two files are used to configure FoxPro -- the DOS CONFIG.SYS configuration file and CONFIG.FP, the FoxPro configuration file.  


           CONFIG.SYS            

The system configuration file, CONFIG.SYS, contains certain commands that are checked and executed when you start up your computer.  These commands change your computer's default configuration.  

CONFIG.SYS is not a FoxPro file.  It's a file that DOS uses to establish the working environment.  Because FoxPro interacts with this environment, you must be sure that certain settings are properly established.  Two CONFIG.SYS statements are of immediate importance to FoxPro:

	BUFFERS	
		The BUFFERS statement contains the number of disk buffers that DOS sets aside in memory when your computer is started.  A disk buffer is a block of memory (typically 512 bytes) that DOS uses to hold data when reading and writing from disk.  For best performance with FoxPro, the CONFIG.SYS file should contain a BUFFERS statement with a number between 20 and 40.

	FILES
		The FILES statement sets the number of files that DOS can open and access at one time.  This number is directly related to the number of files that FoxPro will be able to open.  The FILES statement in CONFIG.SYS should always be at least 10 more than the greatest number of files that will be open at one time in FoxPro.  We recommend a minimum setting of 40.

	See your DOS manual for complete details on the CONFIG.SYS file and the various statements it can contain.
	

           CONFIG.FP             

The FoxPro configuration file, CONFIG.FP, lets you define the FoxPro environment when FoxPro is started.  FoxPro reads each line in the CONFIG.FP file and adjusts itself accordingly.  

When FoxPro is started, it automatically searches for a CONFIG.FP in the following locations:

	1.	The startup APP or EXE, if any.  This would be the case if, for instance, you started FoxPro by typing something like:
		
			FOXPROX myapp.app
		
	2.	The working directory.
	
	3.	The FoxPro directory.

	4.	Along the DOS path.

You can specify the directory where CONFIG.FP resides or specify a file with a name other than CONFIG.FP that will be used as the FoxPro configuration file.  

When you start FoxPro from the DOS command line you can include an optional switch to specify the name and location of the configuration file to be used.  The following line can be used to specify the name and location of the configuration file:

	FOXPRO -C<pathname>\[<file>]

You can also include the following line in your AUTOEXEC.BAT file to specify the name and location of the configuration file:

	SET FOXPROCFG=<pathname>\[<file>]

If you do not include the <file> you must include a backslash (\) after the pathname for FoxPro to recognize an existing CONFIG.FP file.  

If a CONFIG.FP file cannot be located, FoxPro's built-in default settings are used.


 Changing Configuration Settings 

It is simple to change settings in the configuration file using any text editor, especially the built-in FoxPro editor.  The CONFIG.FP text file contains one or more lines with the following format:

	<item> = <value>

	Examples:

	TALK = OFF
	BELL = OFF
	LABEL = LBL
	BLOCKSIZE = 40

Numeric configuration options are checked to ensure that they fall within the range of permissible values for that item.  Incorrect values are automatically changed to the nearest permissible value.  FoxPro ignores any CONFIG.FP statements that are not supported, rather than report an error. 

After your change your CONFIG.FP file, you must QUIT FoxPro and start again before any of these changes take effect.


