  Expanded/Extended Memory,"
     Extended/Expanded Memory    

FoxPro will take advantage of all types of computer memory.  If the computer is configured correctly, FoxPro's performance will be enhanced.

PCs can contain three types of memory:  conventional, expanded and extended.

Conventional Memory
	All PCs can contain conventional memory (up to 640K).  This is the memory that programs typically load into and run in.  The Standard version of FoxPro requires that you have at least 512K of conventional memory with at least 420K of it free after memory resident programs have been loaded.

Expanded Memory
	The 8086 family of microprocessors have a physical address space of 1024K, or 1MB.  The first 640K is the conventional memory space discussed above.  The remaining 384K is reserved for use by read-only memory (RAM) and hardware device controllers.  Also, within this area of memory, a 64K block can be reserved for use by an expanded memory manager which conforms to the Lotus/Intel/Microsoft interface specification (a LIM EMS Memory Manager).

	The Expanded Memory Manager (EMM) administers expanded memory as a system resource that can be used by several applications at the same time and services EMS function calls.  EMS memory is bank-switched memory that can be larger than the CPU's address space that is mapped into conventional memory via the EMS page frame.

Upper Memory Blocks
	The upper 384K of memory which is reserved may have RAM mapped into it via an expanded memory manager on an 80386 or 80486, or a hardware device such as the MAXIT card.
	
	Upper memory blocks are particularly beneficial because they provide more conventional memory to run applications (such as FoxPro) after network shell and Terminate-Stay Resident (TSR) applications are loaded into the upper memory blocks.

Extended Memory
	Extended memory is memory that lies above the 1MB address range.  It can be used directly by some operating systems (OS/2 and UNIX), but standard DOS cannot address it without the use of an Extended Memory Specification (XMS) driver, an interface that allows access to memory beyond 640K.  Applications using this address space must be running in protected mode.


    Memory and Standard FoxPro   

The following suggestions will help you configure a system that optimizes the execution of the Standard version of FoxPro.  For best performance, make as much expanded memory available to FoxPro as possible.

EMS
	If FoxPro is loaded along with memory-resident programs like spoolers or key-redefinition programs, you will want to increase your computer's memory beyond the conventional limit of 640K.

	On machines with expanded memory that is LIM 4.0 EMS compatible, FoxPro uses the first 64K of expanded memory as ""general purpose"" memory and any remaining expanded memory to speed file I/O and to cache FoxPro code segments.  General purpose memory is used to manage Browse windows, user-defined windows, menus, memory variables, programs, etc.

	If you run on an 80386 or 80486 you're in luck!  There are many inexpensive programs that use extended memory to emulate EMS, such as QEMM from Quarterdeck and 386MAX from Qualitas.  MS-DOS 5.0 includes EMM386.

	If you use non-80386 processors you have several options.  First, you could invest in an EMS board.  These pieces of hardware, which usually work with both 8086/88 and 80286 processors, include substantial amounts of memory together with driver programs which provide the software interface to the board.  Most of the boards we've tested work fine so you can probably choose based on price, speed and reputation.

	Software utility programs are also available for 80286 (AT-class) processors that are supposed to use extended memory to emulate EMS.  However, our experience with such products has been discouraging:  we have yet to see one that works with FoxPro.

Between 640K and 1MB
	There are several ways to access memory in the first megabyte above 640K.  Such memory is not contiguous with memory in the lower 640K and many programs can't use it.  However, FoxPro can -- and it's exceedingly valuable general purpose memory.  Additional non-EMS memory beyond 640K speeds FoxPro I/O performance and -- often more important -- significantly expands the maximum number of windows, files, indexes, strings, etc., available.

	If you use an 80386sx, 80386, or 80486 processor, you're in luck.  Most EMS emulators like QEMM and 386MAX will automatically make unused blocks of memory between 640K and 1MB available.  FoxPro will then automatically make use of such memory.

	If you use an 8086/88 or 80286 processor, hardware products are available which can be used to add memory above 640K in unused portions of that address space.  One such board that we've used successfully is the MAXIT board from McGraw-Hill Software.

Beyond 1MB -- Extended Memory
	Extended memory cannot be used directly by the Standard version of FoxPro until it is made to act like EMS.  How you make extended memory act like expanded memory is dependent on your system, but typically you install a memory manager -- software that provides an EMS style (LIM 4.0) interface to extended memory.  Once the extended memory is emulating EMS memory, FoxPro will sense that it is there and make good use of it.

	To check how much EMS is currently being used by FoxPro, look in the About FoxPro box (by choosing About FoxPro... on the System menu popup) or use the function SYS(23).

FoxPro and Older EMS Emulators
	Certain older EMS memory managers cause problems for FoxPro because the emulators do not fully support the LIM 4.0 specification.  Special options are provided to allow FoxPro to operate with incomplete EMS emulators.  These options don't represent the optimum configuration for FoxPro.  (If your EMS driver is not LIM EMS 4.0 compatible, expanded memory can be used only to speed file I/O.)

	If FoxPro behaves strangely and you have an older EMS emulator, add one of the following to your CONFIG.FP file:

	EMS64=OFF
		All expanded memory will be used to speed file I/O.  Try this first.  If you're still having problems, try the option below.

	EMS=64
		All expanded memory is ignored except for the first 64K, which is used as ""general purpose"" memory.

	Specifically, some users with ancient versions of QEMM reported problems running FoxPro.  If you use QEMM, we recommend that you upgrade to the latest version of QEMM.


    Memory and Extended FoxPro   

The Extended version of FoxPro can take advantage of extended memory or extended memory which has been made to act like expanded memory, but it cannot mix and match the two.  If only part of your extended memory is acting like expanded memory, the Extended version will only use the memory that is acting like expanded memory.  For example, if you have 8MB of memory and only 1MB of it is seen as expanded memory, the Extended version of FoxPro will not be able to access the other 7MB.

FoxPro (X) uses a modified version of the Ergo OS386 DOS Extender to run in 386 protected mode.  DOS Extenders are able to operate in a variety of environments.  When the Extender starts up it checks for the presence of any of the following memory environments in this order:

-	DPMI Server (DOS Protected Mode Interface ) - Windows 3.x is a DPMI Server.  If a DPMI server is present, FoxPro Extended cannot load because FoxPro Extended version uses Ergo's OS386 that does not support DPMI at present.  Presently it will, and a revision of FoxPro (X) will be available shortly thereafter which operates directly under DMPI.  

	NOTE:	This does NOT mean you can't run under Windows 3.x.  It simply means that, for the moment, you'll have to run the Standard Version. 

-	VCPI Server (Virtual Control Program Interface) - 386MAX, BlueMax, QEMM-386, EMM386.EXE (not earlier DOS 4 versions of EMM386.SYS), and Compaq's CEMM are VCPI servers.  They also perform various other functions.

-	XMS Driver (eXtended Memory Specification) - Microsoft's HIMEM.SYS, Compaq's HIMEM.EXE, 386MAX, BlueMax and QEMM-386 are XMS drivers. 

-	INT 15 - When no memory manager is present, they use this Interrupt to query extended memory, allocate it, etc.

What this means in practical terms for FoxPro Extended users:

DOS HIMEM.SYS and EMM386.EXE
	If you are using DOS HIMEM.SYS AND EMM386.EXE, EMM386.EXE gets all of its memory from the XMS memory managed by HIMEM.SYS.  Without any parameters, it defaults to providing just 256K of VCPI managed memory (also displayed as EMS).  256K of VCPI managed memory is not sufficient to load FoxPro Extended version.  Even if the other 3MB of extended memory is available as XMS (managed by HIMEM.SYS), OS386 will ignore it.  It only uses the first memory manager it sees (in the order outlined above).

	If you want to use EMM386.EXE with FoxPro Extended version, you must add a numeric parameter in the DEVICE=EMM386.SYS line.  The number should reflect the amount of extended memory on your machine in Kbytes and be a multiple of 16.  If for some reason you get a message (at boot time) about EMM386 adjusting the value, change your CONFIG.SYS file to reflect this value and you won't see that message anymore.

	DO NOT use the NOEMS parameter.  This will also turn off VCPI services that are accessed through EMS.

386MAX, BlueMax and QEMM386
	These VCPI servers share EMS, XMS and VCPI memory using only one manager.  Furthermore, the default value of EMS and VCPI memory is ALL of your available extended memory.  This is why they work perfectly with FoxPro Extended version with no special parameters.

	Also they generally operate faster than EMM386.EXE.  You can test the speed for yourself.  FoxPro's DISPLAY STATUS display shows the remapping speed of your EMS emulator in microseconds.",General cf
