  Printer Driver Hints,"
       Printer Driver Hints      

Here are some hints that may be useful when you create reports or labels and print them with a printer driver setup loaded.  

	Only one printer setup can be active at a time.  For instance, you might specify a printer setup using the Printer Setup menu option on the File menu.  Or you might specify _PDSETUP = ""mysetup"" in a program.

	Report and label forms always have a printer setup specified with them.  If you include the keyword PDSETUP with a REPORT FORM or LABEL FORM command, the printer setup specified in the form is loaded prior to printing the report or labels.  
	
	If you do NOT include PDSETUP with REPORT FORM or LABEL FORM, then the report or label printing is done using the current printer setup at the time the command is executed.

	In the RQBE Display Options dialog, the Use Printer Setup in Report/Label Form check box controls whether or not the REPORT/LABEL FORM command issued by RQBE will include the PDSETUP keyword.

	If you are using a scalable font and lines are spilling onto additional pages, reduce the font size or the number of lines per page.

	When creating a report, if you choose the Right Alignment radio button in the Style dialog for a character field, be sure to also choose the Right Align check box in the Format dialog.

	To right justify a numeric field when a PICTURE clause is used, be sure that the length of the PICTURE clause is identical to the width of the field.  

	If you use TYPE to send a text file to the printer and a printer driver setup is loaded, the appearance of printed output may differ from the text file.  For example, if you are using a proportional font and you use spaces in the text file to align columns of figures, the figures may not align properly in the printed output.

	If you are using a Postscript printer driver supplied with FoxPro, certain characters (ASCII 0 - 3, 127 - 178 and 219 - 255) may not be printed.  The Postscript typeface you specify determines if these characters will be printed.

	If you are using the Postscript printer driver and the printer runs out of paper, you will not receive a ""Printer Not Ready"" error message.

	You can use ? to execute printer driver procedures that are not normally executed.  For example, when you use LIST to send output to the printer, the page start procedure PDPAGEST is not executed.  You can issue ? PDPAGEST() before issuing LIST to initialize printer settings for the current page.

	If you are using GENPD.APP and you don't have a default printer setup, you can reduce the time it takes to load FoxPro by including the line

	PDSETUP = '-'
	
	in your FoxPro CONFIG.FP configuration file.
	
	If your printer isn't included in the P_CODES database supplied with FoxPro, check your printer manual to see if your printer emulates one of the printers included in the P_CODES database.

	If your printer cannot emulate another printer, you can open the P_CODES database and append a blank record.  Insert the proper printer control codes in the appropriate fields in the record.  A description of the fields in the P_CODES database and their contents is listed in the FoxPro Printer Drivers booklet, and printer controls codes are usually listed in the manual that came with your printer.

	After you have entered the printer control codes, close the database and rebuild GENPD.APP, the printer support application included with FoxPro.  You can now choose the printer from the Printers list in the Printer Setup Editing dialog.

	If you are using a HP LaserJet II printer, choosing the 6 Lines per inch radio button in the Printer Setup Editing dialog actually prints 7 lines per inch.  This prevents lines from spilling onto additional pages when you print a Quick Report.  To print 6 lines per inch when you choose this radio button, open the P_CODES database.  In the P_LPI field, replace 7.27 with 8.00 (don't change the other characters in this field).  Close the database and rebuild GENPD.APP, the printer support application included with FoxPro.",General pr
  Problem RAM Disks & Caches,"
    Problem RAM Disks & Caches   

Several products create RAM disks or disk caches using expanded (EMS) memory that are not compatible with FoxPro.  As far as we can determine, the problem is that certain RAM disk or cache software doesn't follow the ""rules of the road"" for EMS.

If you are running a program that creates a RAM disk or disk cache out of EMS, and if data on the RAM disk is damaged, or if (in the case of disk caches) other odd disk behavior is noted, you may have this problem.  We have seen no situations where the symptoms are subtle -- FoxPro has difficulty instantly.  This means that there is little danger of long-term data corruption.

Technical Description

If EMS is ON, FoxPro does much of its I/O directly into EMS, i.e., performs direct memory access input/output (DMA I/O) directly into the EMS page frame.  It appears that FoxPro is one of very few application programs using this technique (although it is a perfectly legitimate and desirable use of EMS specifically encompassed in the EMS specification).

However, RAM disk and disk cache programs (which also perform I/O directly into EMS) conflict with FoxPro's use of EMS.

In the cases we've examined, these other programs have been written under the assumption that nobody else is performing direct EMS I/O.  Here are details of what goes wrong:

-	FoxPro requests that DOS perform an I/O transfer into the EMS page frame.

-	The RAM disk or cache program intercepts this call to DOS and takes appropriate action to effect the I/O data transfer.  We've seen three ways these programs go wrong:

	1.	Some fail to allocate the EMS they're using, causing immediate difficulties when FoxPro tries to use the same memory.

	2.	Some fail to restore the EMS page frame to point to the same memory it did prior to the I/O request.  They fool FoxPro by changing the memory referenced in the page frame during the course of an I/O operation.

	3.	Some fail to note that the addresses into which data will be read are in the page frame itself.  They remap the page frame so it contains their I/O buffers, then copy data from their buffers to the I/O transfer address -- failing to note that this address is in their own buffer.  Of course, this instantly corrupts the data in their buffers.

There's really nothing Fox can do to correct these deviations from proper EMS usage as defined by the LIM 4.0 specification.

What Fox Software Will Do:

-	Test as many of these products as possible to verify correct operation or identify problems

-	Aggressively investigate reports of difficulties

-	Maintain and circulate a list of products known to function correctly and of products for which problems have been reported

-	Work with the publishers of incompatible products to assist them in correcting their products

Of course, if any of these problems are found to originate with FoxPro, or if there are reasonable adjustments that can be made to FoxPro to correct problems, we will make the appropriate changes as quickly as possible.

What You Can Do If You Run Into These Problems

-	If possible, configure your RAM disk or cache utility to use extended, not expanded, memory.

-	Don't use your RAM disk or disk cache program simultaneously with FoxPro.  Neither one has much effect on FoxPro's performance one way or the other.

-	Include EMS=OFF in your CONFIG.FP file.  This solution is not recommended since FoxPro can run more than twice as fast if EMS is available.  Moreover, neither RAM disk nor disk cache programs have much effect on FoxPro's performance.

-	Contact the publisher of your RAM disk or cache software to obtain an updated version.

-	Purchase one of the products which we have verified operate correctly with FoxPro.",General cf
