  Project Manager Hints,"
      Project Manager Hints      

This topic discusses common questions about the Project Manager.

Unknown References in Projects
	Occasionally, when you build a project, the Project Manager alerts you that it can't find a file or an array that is referenced in the project.  In this case, you can do one of the following:

	-	Make sure the names are spelled correctly, and that the file/array does exist.

	-	Add an EXTERNAL command to the appropriate location so that FoxPro automatically includes the file or finds the array, then build the project.

	-	In the case of a file, manually add the file to the project, then build the project.
	
	-	Temporarily ignore the message and build the project without resolving the reference.  This will usually not cause problems with an application but may cause problems with an executable file.

When to use the EXTERNAL Command
	EXTERNAL is used to include files and resolve undefined references in a project created by the FoxPro Project Manager.  EXTERNAL is used only by the Project Manager, and is ignored during program execution.

	A file specified with EXTERNAL will be included in a project by the Project Manager.  You must include a key word (LABEL, LIBRARY, MENU, PROCEDURE, REPORT or SCREEN) before the file name to tell the Project Manager the type of file to include in the project.
	
	For example, when an array is passed to a UDF or procedure, you may need to identify the array in the UDF or procedure for the Project Manager.  To do this, you can use the EXTERNAL ARRAY command as in the example below.

	*	Create an array
	DIMENSION firstarray(2)
		
	*	Name of array used in the UDF
	EXTERNAL ARRAY arraytwo
		
	SET TALK OFF
	STORE 10 TO firstarray(1)
	STORE 10 TO firstarray(2)
		
	*	Pass array by reference to a UDF
	= ADDTWO(@firstarray)
	
	FUNCTION ADDTWO
	PARAMETER arraytwo
	CLEAR
	arraytwo(1) = arraytwo(1) + 2
	arraytwo(2) = arraytwo(2) + 2
	?arraytwo(1)
	?arraytwo(2)

	The Project Manager must also be alerted to a file name contained in a name expression or in macro substitution.  This assures that all necessary files are included in a project when the project is built.  It must also be alerted to arrays that are created in another procedure or a UDF.

	For more information on name expressions, see the Name Expressions topic.  Whenever possible, use a name expression instead of macro substitution to improve performance.

	A description of each key word follows:
	
	ARRAY	Use when an array is created in a program and then used in a lower level program.

	LABEL	Tells the Project Manager that the <file name> you include in indirect file reference or macro substitution is a label definition file.

	LIBRARY	Use when a library file name is referenced by indirect file referencing or macro substitution.

	MENU	Use if a menu definition file is included in an indirect file reference or macro substitution.

	PROCEDURE	Use to identify an external procedure or UDF that is included in an indirect file reference or macro substitution.  

	REPORT	Tells the Project Manager that the <file name> you include in indirect file reference or macro substitution is a report definition file.

	SCREEN	Use if a screen definition file is included in an indirect file reference or macro substitution.

Including/Excluding Files
	All files referenced by an application should be part of a project.  When you build an application from a project, all files in the project that can be executed (programs, screens, menus) are combined as part of the application code.  Files that can't be executed, such as reports, labels and databases, can also be included in the application in read-only form.

	If you want your users to be able to modify any non-executable files in the project, you can select the file in the Project window and choose Exclude from the Project menu popup.  A  appears in the Project window next to the selected file name.

	Excluded files are listed in the Project window for your reference but must be distributed in addition to the application if needed by the application.

	You should exclude any files such as databases, indexes, reports and labels that you want the end user to be able to modify.  You'll probably want to include help databases and databases that contain look up information to prevent users from modifying them.

	If you change your mind and want to include a file you excluded, select the file in the Project window and choose Include from the Project menu popup.

Projects with Common Files
	If several projects share the same screens and/or menus or files, you may find that you get ""Source out of date"" messages while debugging.  Make sure you rebuild the project before debugging or use the Project Options dialog to put each project's generated code into its own directory.

Home Directory
	If you get ""Source not found"" error while debugging or an unexpected ""File not found"" error while running your application, your home directory may be incorrect.  Make sure that the home directory is set to be the place where the application will run from and that the application is built into that directory.  For example, if C:\FOXPRO2\MYAPP is your home directory, build the application into C:\FOXPRO2\MYAPP.

Build Executable Disabled
	If the Build Executable is disabled in the Build Option dialog, either you do not have the Distribution Kit installed or it is not installed properly.




