",Command en
SET SYSMENU,"
           SET SYSMENU           

SET SYSMENU ON | OFF | AUTOMATIC  
	| TO [<System menu popup list 
	| pad list>] | TO [DEFAULT]


Controls access to System menu bar.
Default value - ON


ON
	System menu bar is accessible during program execution when SET SYSMENU is ON and FoxPro is waiting for keyboard input (during BROWSE, READ, MODIFY COMMAND, etc.).  The System menu bar isn't displayed, but may be displayed and made accessible by pressing the Alt or F10 keys or by double clicking the right mouse button.

OFF
	Access to System menu bar is not available any time during program execution.

AUTOMATIC
	Setting SYSMENU to AUTOMATIC within a program makes the System menu bar visible during program execution.  System menu bar is accessible as appropriate, and menu options are enabled and disabled as appropriate for the current command.  

TO [<System menu popup list>] 
TO [<pad list>] 
TO [DEFAULT]
	Place a subset of System menu popups into the System menu bar by including a System menu popup list or pad list.  The TO <System menu popup list | pad list> clause can contain any combination of System menu popup or pad names separated by commas.

DEFAULT
	If you have modified the System menu bar or its popups it may be restored to its default configuration with SET SYSMENU TO DEFAULT.



See Also:  DEFINE BAR, DEFINE MENU, DEFINE PAD, DEFINE POPUP, POP MENU, PUSH MENU, SET STICKY 

",Command pe ex
SET TALK,"
            SET TALK             

SET TALK  ON | OFF |
	WINDOW [<window name>]
	| NOWINDOW


Direct command processing information to screen or window.
Default value - ON


ON
	If talk was SET OFF and is then SET ON, talk is directed to same location before it was SET OFF.

OFF
	Use SET TALK OFF to prevent talk from being sent to screen or to a system or user-defined window.

WINDOW [<window name>]
	If you specify SET TALK WINDOW, talk is displayed in upper right corner of screen in system message window if SET NOTIFY is ON.  

	When you type or move mouse, system message window is removed.  

	You can direct talk to a user-defined window by including a <window name> after the WINDOW keyword.  You must create the user-defined window with DEFINE WINDOW before directing talk to it.  A user-defined window does not have to be active or visible to direct talk to it.

NOWINDOW
	Issuing SET TALK NOWINDOW directs talk to the screen.

TALK reporting interval can be specified with SET ODOMETER.  


         Program Example         

The following program example demonstrates how you can save the TALK setting without generating talk on the screen or in a window.  

IF SET('TALK') = 'ON'  && TALK handled as a special case.
	SET TALK OFF          && Turn TALK OFF 
	savetalk = 'ON'       && TALK was ON, save the setting 
ELSE   && TALK is OFF 
	savetalk = 'OFF'      && TALK was OFF, save the setting
ENDIF

row =    INT((SROWS() - 14) / 2)
column = INT((SCOLS() - 80) / 2)

SET TALK &savetalk   && Restore original TALK setting

=sys(2017)
@ row,      column + 1  FILL TO row+3,  column + 16 COLOR GR+/B
@ row + 4,  column + 1  FILL TO row+10, column + 8  COLOR GR+/B
@ row + 4,  column + 10 FILL TO row+10, column + 22 COLOR R+/B
@ row + 4,  column + 23 FILL TO row+10, column + 35 COLOR R/B
@ row,      column + 36 FILL TO row+10, column + 50 COLOR BG/B
@ row + 4,  column + 51 FILL TO row+10, column + 63 COLOR G/B
@ row + 4,  column + 64 FILL TO row+10, column + 79 COLOR B+/B
@ row + 11, column      FILL TO row+14, column + 79 COLOR W/B 



See Also:  DEFINE WINDOW, SET ODOMETER, SYS(103) TALK setting, _TALLY

",Command en er
SET TEXTMERGE,"
          SET TEXTMERGE          

SET TEXTMERGE 
	[ON | OFF]
	[TO [<file>] [ADDITIVE]]
	[WINDOW <window name>]
	[SHOW | NOSHOW]


Enables or disables evaluation of database fields.
Default value - OFF


SET TEXTMERGE determines how database fields, memory variables, functions or expressions surrounded by text merge delimiters are evaluated.  SET TEXTMERGE also lets you direct text merge output to screen or a window and to a file.

ON
	If TEXTMERGE is SET ON, any database fields, memory variables, functions and expressions surrounded by text merge delimiters are evaluated and output when placed after \ or \\ commands or between TEXT and ENDTEXT.  

OFF
	If TEXTMERGE is SET OFF, any database fields, memory variables, functions and expressions are literally output along with text merge delimiters enclosing them.

TO [<file>] [ADDITIVE]
	By default, output from \, \\ and TEXT ... ENDTEXT is sent to screen.  You may also direct the output to a text file by including FILE with a <file> name.  If a file with that name doesn't exist a new file is created; if a file with same name already exists you are given the option of overwriting the existing file.  

	You may append output from \, \\ and TEXT ... ENDTEXT to end of an existing file by including ADDITIVE keyword.  

WINDOW <window name>
	Output from \, \\ and TEXT ... ENDTEXT is directed to screen by default.  You may redirect output to a window by including WINDOW.  Include the <window name> where output will be directed.  Window must first be created with DEFINE WINDOW before output may be sent to it, but the window does not have to be active.

SHOW | NOSHOW
	Output generated by \, \\ and TEXT ... ENDTEXT is sent to screen or in a window by default.  Output to the screen or a window may be suppressed entirely by including the NOSHOW keyword.  To display text merge output again, include the SHOW keyword in SET TEXTMERGE.  The startup default is SHOW.  

Memo fields and Text Merge
	Memo fields can be used to nest text merge.  If a memo field contains database field names, memory variables, functions or expressions surrounded by current text merge delimiters, they are evaluated and output with contents of the memo field.  Memo field name must also be enclosed in text merge delimiters.


             Examples            

The following short program example (run on the Fourth of July) demonstrates how the contents of the variable MTODAYDATE and the DATE() and TIME() functions are evaluated when TEXTMERGE is SET ON.  The variable, DATE() and TIME() are evaluated since they are enclosed by the text merge delimiters and TEXTMERGE is SET ON.  The output is sent to the screen: 

CLEAR
SET TALK OFF
STORE 'Today is: ' TO mtodaydate
SET TEXTMERGE ON
\<<mtodaydate>>
\\<<DATE()>>
\The time is:
\\ <<TIME()>>

Here is the output from the program above:

Today is: 07/04/90
The time is: 10:55:19

In the following example, the NOTES memo field in the CLIENTS database from the ORGANIZER application is replaced with the DATE() and TIME() functions surrounded by the default textmerge delimiters.  The memo field is then evaluated.

SELECT 0
USE CLIENTS
CLEAR
REPLACE notes WITH '<<DATE()>> <<TIME()>>'
\<<notes>>
USE

Try this example after removing the text merge delimiters from around the functions in the memo field, and then after removing the delimiters from around the memo field name.



See Also:  _PRETEXT, SET TEXTMERGE DELIMITERS, _TEXT, TEXT ... ENDTEXT

",Command tm fi pe nx
SET TEXTMERGE DELIMITERS,"
    SET TEXTMERGE DELIMITERS     

SET TEXTMERGE DELIMITERS 
	TO [<expC1> [, <expC2>]]
	

Specifies text merge delimiters.
Default value - << and >>


The current TEXTMERGE delimiters can be displayed with DISPLAY STATUS.

<expC1> [, <expC2>]
	If you specify one delimiter by including <expC1>, both left and right delimiters will be set to <expC1>.  If you specify both delimiters by including <expC1> and <expC2>, left delimiter will be set to <expC1> and right delimiter to <expC2>.  

If you issue the command SET TEXTMERGE DELIMITERS TO without any additional arguments,  default delimiters (<< and >>) are restored.  Left or right default delimiter or both can also be restored to default by specifying  null string in <expC1> or <expC2> or both.



See Also:  \ | \\, SET TEXTMERGE, _TEXT, TEXT ... ENDTEXT

