_TALLY		N		0
_TEXT		C		Null string
_THROTTLE	N		0
_WRAP 		L 		.F.



See Also:  PUBLIC, PRIVATE, STORE 

",Sysmemvar mv
_ALIGNMENT,"
      _ALIGNMENT = <expC>        



Determines how output is aligned between current margins.


<expC> MUST be one of these:

LEFT 		left justified (default)
CENTER		centered
RIGHT		right justified 
	
Only active when _WRAP is set to true (.T.).



See Also:  @ ... SAY/GET, _LMARGIN, _RMARGIN, _WRAP

",Sysmemvar pr
_BOX,"
          _BOX = <expL>          



Display boxes in printed output.


Determines whether boxes (as specified with DEFINE BOX command) will be displayed around lines of text.  This system variable applies only to the boxes that will be created with the DEFINE BOX command.  



See Also:  @ ... BOX, @ ... TO, DEFINE BOX

",Sysmemvar pr
_CALCMEM,"
        _CALCMEM = <expN>        



Value stored in Calculator's memory.


Note that the Calculator's memory is stored in the FoxPro resource file; exiting FoxPro does not reset the Calculator's memory to a default value.

For additional information on the Calculator, see the FoxPro Interface Guide.


         Program Example         

Below, the numeric constant  is stored to _CALCMEM.  The Calculator is then displayed and the keyboard is stuffed with the letter R.  The keystroke R displays the value that is stored in the Calculator's memory. 

STORE PI() TO _CALCMEM
ACTIVATE WINDOW calculator
CLEAR TYPEAHEAD
KEYBOARD CHR(82)



See Also:  STORE

",Sysmemvar da
_CALCVALUE,"
       _CALCVALUE = <expN>       



Value displayed by Calculator.


Note that the Calculator's displayed value is stored in the FoxPro resource file; exiting FoxPro does not reset the Calculator's display to a default value.

For additional information on the Calculator, see the FoxPro Interface Guide.


         Program Example         

Below, the numeric value 2.7183 is stored to _CALCVALUE.  The Calculator is displayed and initialized to the value previously stored, 2.7183.

STORE 2.7183 TO _CALCVALUE
ACTIVATE WINDOW calculator



See Also:  STORE

",Sysmemvar da
_CLIPTEXT,"
         _CLIPTEXT = <expC>      



Returns or initializes the contents of the clipboard, a temporary storage area for text.

 
When text is copied or cut from a text editing area it's placed on the clipboard.  The contents of the clipboard can then be pasted into another text editing area.  With the _CLIPTEXT system memory variable you can return the contents of the clipboard or STORE a character expression on the clipboard.  

Some examples of where text may be cut, copied or pasted are the FoxPro text editor, memo editing windows, the Browse or Debug windows, dialogs, the expression builder and active GETs.  With the Capture desk accessory any text displayed on the screen or in a window may be copied to the clipboard.

_CLIPTEXT contains the contents of the clipboard.  You may place a character expression <expC> on the clipboard with the STORE command or the = assignment operator.  _CLIPTEXT, like any other character memory variable, may contain up to 65,504 characters.  _CLIPTEXT by default is a PUBLIC memory variable; it may be declared PRIVATE.
 

         Program Example         

The program example below displays 25 lines from the clipboard in a movable window at the bottom of the screen.  An outline window is created in which another window displaying the clipboard is scrolled up or down.  Additional lines of the clipboard may be viewed by pressing the up or down arrow keys, and the window may be removed from the screen by waiting 5 seconds, clicking the mouse or pressing any key.  

*** Clipboard display example ***

*** Initialize variables & Define windows ***

SET TALK OFF
STORE 1 TO windtop
STORE _CLIPTEXT TO ctext

IF LEN(ctext) > 2100		&& Make clipboard the size of our window
	STORE SUBSTR(ctext, 1, 2100) TO ctext
ENDIF

STORE STRTRAN(ctext, CHR(9), SPACE(4), 1) to ctext 		&& Insert tabs

*** Define an outline & and scrolling window to show the clipboard ***

DEFINE WINDOW outline FROM 21,-1 to 25,80;	
	TITLE "" Clipboard "" CLOSE 

DEFINE WINDOW clipwind FROM -1,-1 TO 25,80

ACTIVATE WINDOW outline
ACTIVATE WINDOW clipwind IN outline 	&& Place window in a frame window

*** Show the clipboard in the clipboard window ***

IF EMPTY(ctext) 						&& Clipboard empty
	@ 0,0 SAY ""Clipboard is empty!""
ELSE	
	IF AT(chr(13),ctext) = 0			&& No carriage returns (CR)
		@ 0,0 SAY ctext					&& Show clipboard
	ELSE
		STORE AT(CHR(13), ctext, 1) to crpos1 	&& 1st CR
		
		*** Show 1st clipboard line ***
		
		@ 0,0 SAY SUBSTR(SUBSTR(ctext, 1, crpos1 - 1), 1, 80)  
		
		FOR lineno = 1 to 24
			STORE AT(CHR(13), ctext, lineno + 1) to crpos2 		&& Next CR

			*** The next 2 lines shows each additional clipboard line ***			

			@ lineno,0 SAY SUBSTR(SUBSTR(ctext, crpos1 + 1, ;
				(crpos2 - crpos1) - 1),1,80)
		 	
		 	STORE crpos2 to crpos1		

		NEXT  		Loop for next clipboard line
	ENDIF			Test for 0 or more carriage returns (CR)
ENDIF				Test for empty clipboard

DO WHILE .T.		&& Test for up or down arrows, mouse click, any key
	
	keyval = INKEY(5,""MH"") 		&& Check for key press, mouse click
								&& or 5 seconds
								
	IF keyval = 24 AND BETWEEN(windtop,1,23)		&& Down arrow
		MOVE WINDOW clipwind BY -1,0		&& Move clipboard window up
		windtop = windtop + 1
	ENDIF	
	IF keyval = 5 AND BETWEEN(windtop,2,24)		&& Up arrow
		MOVE WINDOW clipwind BY 1,0			&& Move clipboard window down
		windtop = windtop - 1
	ENDIF	
	IF keyval <> 5 AND keyval <> 24 		&& Some other key, quit out
		CLEAR WINDOWS 
		SET TALK ON
		EXIT
	ENDIF
ENDDO



See Also:  PUBLIC, PRIVATE, STORE 

",Sysmemvar en
_CUROBJ,"
         _CUROBJ = <expN>        



The number of the currently selected GET object.  


GET objects are created with the @ ... GET command including fields, check boxes, push and invisible buttons, popups, lists and text editing regions.

The GET object number is determined by the order the GETs are issued.  Each individual button in a set of push, radio and invisible buttons is considered a separate object. 

The value of _CUROBJ can be changed to reposition the cursor to another GET object.  This is typically done in VALID and WHEN routines.


         Program Example         

CLEAR
SET TALK OFF
STORE 1 to x, y, z

ON KEY LABEL F2 @ 14,2 SAY 'Object # ' + LTRIM(STR(_CUROBJ)) && Show #

@ 4,2 GET x  PICTURE '@*R \<Apples;\<Oranges;\<Limes'     && Radio 

@ 2,2 GET y  && Get field
@ 8,2 GET z  PICTURE '@^ \<Pears;\<Bananas;\<Pineapples'  && Popup

READ CYCLE

ON KEY LABEL F2  && Reset F2 key to default



See Also:  @ ... SAY/GET, OBJNUM(), READ, SHOW GET, SHOW OBJECT 

",Sysmemvar in nx
_DBLCLICK,"
        _DBLCLICK = <expN>       



Time interval FoxPro uses to check for a double or triple mouse click.


For example, if _DBLCLICK is set to 0.5 seconds, you have 1/2 second to click twice for a double click, and 1 second to click 3 times for a triple click.

The larger the value of _DBLCLICK, the longer you may wait between clicking the mouse twice for FoxPro to interpret the two clicks as a double click.  If _DBLCLICK is set to a very small value even quick double (or triple) clicks may be interpreted as two (or three) single clicks.  

The default value for _DBLCLICK is 0.5 seconds.


         Program Example         

This example shows how you can detect a single or double mouse click:

*** Double click detection example ***

*** Establish the program environment ***

SET TALK OFF
SET ESCAPE OFF
CLEAR

*** Create and open a window ***

DEFINE WINDOW MOUSECHK FROM 4,4 TO 20,75 DOUBLE
ACTIVATE WINDOW MOUSECHK
@ 6,16 SAY ""Press a key or click the mouse to start""
@ 8,16 SAY ""      or press the Esc key to quit""

INVAL1 = 0			&& Initialize inkey memory variable

*** Main program loop ***

DO WHILE .T.
	INVAL1 = INKEY(.06,""HM"") && Get INKEY(), hide cursor, check the mouse
		IF INVAL1 = 0  	&& No key or mouse press
		LOOP
	ENDIF		&& Esc key pressed, exit main loop
	IF INVAL1 = 27
		EXIT
	ENDIF
	IF INVAL1 = 151							&& Mouse single clicked
		ROW = MROW()						&& Get mouse pointer position
		COL = MCOL()
		TIMELIMIT = SECONDS() + _DBLCLICK 	&& Time for double mouse click
		INVAL2 = 0
		DO WHILE SECONDS() < TIMELIMIT  	&& Check for double mouse click
			INVAL2 = INKEY(""HM"")
			
*** Double mouse click and mouse pointer inside window ***			
			
			IF INVAL2 = 151 AND COL != -1 AND ROW != -1   
				CLEAR
				@ 7,11 SAY ""Double click at ""
				?? ""Row "" + ALLTRIM(STR(ROW)) + "", Column "" ; 
				+ ALLTRIM(STR(COL)) + "" of this window""
				EXIT
			ENDIF
		ENDDO

*** Single mouse click and mouse pointer inside window ***			

		IF INVAL2 = 0 AND COL != -1 AND ROW != -1
			CLEAR
			@ 7,11 SAY ""Single click at ""
			?? ""Row "" + ALLTRIM(STR(ROW)) + "", Column "" ; 
			+ ALLTRIM(STR(COL)) + "" of this window""
		ENDIF 

*** Mouse pointer outside of window ***			

		IF COL = -1 OR ROW = -1
			CLEAR
			@ 7,17 SAY ""Mouse clicked outside of this window""
			LOOP
		ENDIF
	ENDIF

*** Keyboard character pressed ***			

	IF INVAL1 # 151 AND BETWEEN(INVAL1, 0, 256) 	&& Legal CHR() values
		CLEAR
		@ 7,18 SAY ""Character typed:""
		?? "" "" + CHR(INVAL1) + "", ASCII code "" + ALLTRIM(STR(INVAL1))
    ENDIF

ENDDO  	End of Main loop

*** Restore original environment ***

SET TALK ON
SET ESCAPE ON
CLEAR WINDOWS

*** End of program ***



See Also:  INKEY(), MCOL(), MDOWN(), MROW() 

",Sysmemvar en
_DIARYDATE,"
       _DIARYDATE = <expD>       



Selected date in Calendar/Diary.  


By default the current date is stored in _DIARYDATE.  When the Calendar/Diary is opened the current date will be selected.  A different date may be stored to _DIARYDATE and the Calendar/Diary will be opened with this new date selected.  

Selecting a date other than the currently selected date while the Calendar/Diary is open stores the new date to _DIARYDATE.  If the Calendar/Diary is closed _DIARYDATE will contain the last selected date.


         Program Example         

In this example, the Calendar/Diary is opened with October 31, 2001 selected and the value of _DIARYDATE is displayed.  The DATE() function is used to select the current date, and _DIARYDATE is displayed.  July 4, 1776 is then stored to _DIARYDATE and _DIARYDATE is again displayed.

CLEAR
SET TALK OFF
SET CENTURY ON
STORE {10/31/2001} TO _DIARYDATE
@ 24,0 SAY _DIARYDATE
ACTIVATE WINDOW calendar
WAIT WINDOW
STORE DATE() TO _DIARYDATE
@ 24,16 SAY _DIARYDATE
WAIT WINDOW
STORE {07/04/1776} TO _DIARYDATE
@ 24,32 SAY _DIARYDATE



See Also:  STORE

 ",Sysmemvar da
_GENGRAPH,"
   _GENGRAPH = <program name>    



FoxPro program used by FoxGraph for RQBE results.


_GENGRAPH allows you to specify the program (and its location) that FoxPro uses to output RQBE query results to FoxGraph.  By default, _GENGRAPH uses GENGRAPH.PRG.  You can include a fully qualified path with the program name.

Queries are created in the RQBE window.  In the RQBE window you can specify where the results of a query are directed.  Query results can be directed to a graph created with FoxGraph, the optional graphing package.  For further information on creating a query in the RQBE window, see the FoxPro Getting Started manual or the File Menu chapter in the Interface Guide.



See Also:  CREATE QUERY, _GENXTAB, SELECT - SQL

",Sysmemvar in nx
_GENMENU,"
    _GENMENU = <program name>    



FoxPro program used to generate menu code.


_GENMENU lets you specify the program that FoxPro uses to generate menu code from a .MNX database.  By default, _GENMENU uses GENMENU.PRG.

You can include a fully qualified path with the menu generation program name.



See Also:  CREATE MENU, _GENSCRN

",Sysmemvar mp pr nx
_GENPD,"
         _GENPD = <expC>         



Printer driver interface program.


The system memory variable _GENPD contains the name of the current printer driver interface program.  By default, this program is the application supplied with FoxPro, GENPD.APP.  

The program whose name is stored in _GENPD is executed when any of these five events occur:

 The Printer Driver Setup check box is chosen in the Printer Setup... dialog

 Choose the Set Printer Driver check box in the Report Page Layout or Label Environment dialogs.

 SET PDSETUP is issued 

 A printer driver setup name is stored in _PDSETUP

 A default printer setup has been specified and FoxPro is started

If you store the name of your printer driver interface program in  _GENPD, your program is executed when one of these events occurs.

If you do not include an extension with your printer driver setup program when you store its name in _GENPD, FoxPro looks for and executes a version of the program in the following order:

 An executable (.EXE) version of the program

 An application (.APP) version of the program 

 A compiled (.FXP) version of the program 

 The program (.PRG)  

The printer driver interface program you specify in _GENPD can take virtually any form, but it must have a PARAMETERS statement as its first line.  Two parameters are passed to the program from FoxPro.  The first is a numeric value.  0 is passed to the program if the program is executed by choosing the Printer Driver Setup check box in the Printer Setup dialog, SET PDSETUP is issued or a printer driver setup name is stored in _PDSETUP.  2 is passed to the program if the Set Printer Driver check box is chosen in the Report or Label dialogs.

You can test the numeric parameter passed to the printer driver setup program to prevent recursion.  For example, you store a printer driver program name in _PDRIVER, executing the PDONLOAD procedure in the printer driver program.  Your PDONLOAD procedure executes your printer setup interface application and passes it a value of 1.

The printer setup interface application tests the numeric value.  If it is 1, a printer driver program name should not be stored in _PDRIVER in the program.  If, in this case, a printer driver program name is stored in _PDRIVER, PDONLOAD is executed again, your printer driver setup program is executed again and an infinite loop is created.

The second parameter passed to the printer driver setup program is the name of the printer driver setup specified in the SET PDSETUP command or stored to _PDSETUP.  If the printer driver setup program is executed by choosing the Printer Driver Setup check box in the Printer Setup dialog, a question mark (?) is passed as the second parameter to the program specified in _GENPD.



See Also:  _PDRIVER, _PDSETUP, SET PDSETUP, SET PRINTER

",Sysmemvar pr nx nx
_GENSCRN,"
     _GENSCRN = <program name>   



FoxPro program used to generate screen code.


_GENSCRN lets you specify the program that FoxPro uses to generate screen code from a .SCX database.  By default, _GENSCRN uses GENSCRN.PRG.

You can include a fully qualified path with the screen generation program name.



See Also:  CREATE SCREEN, _GENMENU

",Sysmemvar in nx
_GENXTAB,"
     _GENXTAB = <program name>   



FoxPro program used to generate cross tabs.


_GENXTAB allows you to specify the program and its location that FoxPro uses to output RQBE results to FoxGraph, a report form or a table in cross tabulated format.  _GENXTAB is only used when the cross-tabulate option is selected.

By default, _GENXTAB uses the program GENXTAB.PRG.



See Also:  CREATE QUERY, _GENGRAPH, SELECT - SQL

",Sysmemvar in nx
_INDENT,"
         _INDENT = <expN>        



Indentation.


The number of characters that FoxPro indents (or outdents) the first line of each paragraph from the left margin.

The value of _INDENT can range from the negative value of _LMARGIN to the length of the line minus one ((_RMARGIN - _LMARGIN) - 1).  Positive _INDENT values will cause the output line to be indented.  Negative values will cause the line to be outdented.  _INDENT is 0 by default.

Only active when _WRAP is set to true (.T.).



See Also:  _LMARGIN, _PLOFFSET, _RMARGIN, SET MARGIN, _WRAP 

",Sysmemvar pr
_LMARGIN,"
        _LMARGIN = <expN>        



Position of the left margin for output generated with the ? command.


Only active when _WRAP is set to true (.T.).



See Also:  ???, _INDENT, _PLOFFSET, _RMARGIN, SET MARGIN, _WRAP 

",Sysmemvar pr
_MLINE,"
         _MLINE = <expN>         



MLINE() function's memo field offset.


The MLINE() function is used to return lines from memo fields.  Whenever the MLINE() function is called, MLINE() stores the location of its memo field offset to the _MLINE system memory variable.  _MLINE may be used as the second numeric argument in the MLINE() function to increase the performance of MLINE().

The startup default value for _MLINE is 0.  Be sure to reset _MLINE to 0 before using _MLINE again with the MLINE() function.

For additional information about the use of _MLINE and an example of its use, see the MLINE() function in this help facility.


             Example             

CLEAR
SET TALK OFF
SET MEMOWIDTH TO 50

USE customer  && Open customer database
APPEND BLANK  && Add a record

@2,2 SAY 'Filling memo field...'

*** Fill the memo field  ***

FOR outerloop = 1 TO 5  &&  loop 5 times
	FOR alphabet = 65 TO 90  &&  letters A to Z
		REPLACE comments WITH REPLICATE(CHR(alphabet), 40) ;
			+ CHR(13) ADDITIVE
	NEXT
NEXT

*** Display all lines from the memo field ***

STORE MEMLINES(comments) TO numlines  && Number of lines in memo field

STORE SECONDS() TO begin     &&  Beginning time

FOR count = 1 TO numlines    &&  Loop for number of lines in memo field
	?MLINE(comments, count)  &&  Display each line
NEXT

? STR(SECONDS() - begin, 4, 2) + ' seconds'  && Total time

*** Preferable method using _MLINE in MLINE() ***
*** Display all lines from the memo field ***

WAIT 'Press a key to see the preferred method' WINDOW

CLEAR
STORE 0 TO _MLINE         && Reset _MLINE to zero
STORE SECONDS() TO begin  &&  Beginning time

FOR count = 1 TO numlines        &&  Loop for number of lines in memo field 
	?MLINE(comments, 1, _MLINE)  &&  Display each line
NEXT

? STR(SECONDS() - begin, 4, 2) + ' seconds'  && Total time

SET TALK ON



See Also:  MEMLINES(), MLINE(), SET MEMOWIDTH  

",Sysmemvar db
_PADVANCE,"
        _PADVANCE = <expC>       



Page advance method.


Determines whether FoxPro will advance to the top of a page by using a formfeed character or by using linefeeds.

<expC> 
	MUST be one of these:
		FORMFEED
		LINEFEED

When calculating how many linefeeds to send, FoxPro uses the formula (_PLENGTH - _PLINENO):

 When the EJECT PAGE command is issued without an ON PAGE handler.

 When the EJECT PAGE command is issued with an ON PAGE handler and the line position is greater than the ON PAGE line value.

 When the commands PRINTJOB or ENDPRINTJOB cause _PEJECT to send a page eject to the printer.

However, the formula (_PLENGTH - MOD(PROW(), _PLENGTH)) is used:

 When the EJECT command is issued.

 When the SET DEVICE TO PRINTER command is issued and a subsequent @ ... SAY/GET forces an eject.

Despite the setting of _PADVANCE, you can always send a formfeed character to the printer by outputting a CHR(12).



See Also:  EJECT, _PEJECT, _PLENGTH, _PLINENO, PROW()

",Sysmemvar pr
_PAGENO,"
         _PAGENO = <expN>        



Current page number.


This system memory variable, like all the others, can be reset by providing a value that ranges from 1 to 32,767.  Note that _PAGENO, _PBPAGE and _PEPAGE work in unison.  If _PAGENO is reset (or incremented) such that it falls outside the range of _PBPAGE to _PEPAGE, FoxPro will not print any pages.



See Also:  ON PAGE, _PBPAGE, _PEPAGE, _PLENGTH, _PLINENO

",Sysmemvar pr
_PBPAGE,"
         _PBPAGE = <expN>        



First page to print.


_PBPAGE contains a numeric value that determines the first page to print.  While _PBPAGE is greater than _PAGENO, FoxPro doesn't print.  Instead, it produces pages internally and increments _PAGENO and other system memory variables.  When _PAGENO reaches (or exceeds) the value of _PBPAGE, printing begins.

_PBPAGE values may range from 1 to 32,767.  The startup default is 1.  The value of _PBPAGE must be less than or equal to _PEPAGE.



See Also:  _PAGENO, _PEPAGE, PRINTJOB ... ENDPRINTJOB

",Sysmemvar pr
_PCOLNO,"
         _PCOLNO = <expN>        



Current column position.


Establishes current column position and is used to determine next column address for output.

_PCOLNO contains a numeric value that establishes the current column position and is used to determine the next column address for output.  As FoxPro sends output to the print device, it automatically increments the _PCOLNO value to indicate the current column position.  You can assign any integer value to _PCOLNO, from 0 to 255, in order to position output to a desired column.  (Assigning a value to _PCOLNO has the same effect as using the AT clause of the ? command.)

Unlike the PCOL() function which returns the current position of the printhead and does not change if SET PRINTER is OFF, _PCOLNO changes whenever output is generated -- the SET PRINTER command has no effect on the _PCOLNO value.

PRINTING TIP: When sending output to the printer with SET PRINTER ON, you can cause the printhead to backspace and overstrike previously printed output by manipulating the _PCOLNO value.  To do so, _WRAP must be set to .F. and _PCOLNO must be assigned an appropriate value that's less than the current value.

CAUTION: If _WRAP is set to true (.T.), assigning a _PCOLNO value that's less than the current value will cause text in the internal buffer to be overwritten.  In that instance, the previous text is replaced and not output.



See Also:  ???, PCOL(), _PLINENO, SET PRINTER

",Sysmemvar pr
_PCOPIES,"
        _PCOPIES = <expN>        



Number of copies of the output that will be printed.


This system memory variable can be given a value from 1 to 32,767.  The startup default is 1.  The _PCOPIES variable requires the PRINTJOB ... ENDPRINTJOB command structure and therefore, can only be used in FoxPro programs.  The _PCOPIES assignment statement should be placed before the PRINTJOB command when setting the number of copies to be printed.



See Also:  PRINTJOB ... ENDPRINTJOB

",Sysmemvar pr
_PDRIVER,"
        _PDRIVER = <expC>        



Specifies a printer driver program.  


Storing the name of a printer driver program to _PDRIVER unloads the current printer driver program if one is loaded.  When you store a printer driver program name in _PDRIVER, the PDONUNLOAD procedure in the currently loaded printer driver program is executed (if it has a PDONUNLOAD procedure).  The printer driver you store to _PDRIVER is then loaded, and its PDONLOAD procedure is executed (if it has a PDONLOAD procedure).

When you store a printer driver program to _PDRIVER, the system message ""Printer driver installed"" is displayed.  This message can be suppressed by issuing the command

SET NOTIFY OFF

before you store a printer driver program name to _PDRIVER.



See Also:  SET PRINTER, _PDSETUP

",Sysmemvar pr
_PDSETUP,"
        _PDSETUP = <expC>        



Specify a printer driver setup.


_PDSETUP loads a printer driver setup or clears the current printer driver setup.  A printer driver setup is a combination of settings that include the printer driver program and printing information such as page orientation, default font size and style, margins and so on.

Printer driver setups are stored in your FOXUSER.DBF resource file, and can be created interactively and assigned a name in the Printer Setup Editing dialog.  

A printer driver setup can also be loaded or cleared with SET PDSETUP.

To load a printer driver setup, store the name of the setup in _PDSETUP.  You can clear the current printer driver setup by storing the null string in _PDSETUP.  Storing the null string in _PDSETUP also clears the _PDPARMS array from memory.

If the printer driver setup name you store in _PDSETUP does not exist in your resource file, the current printer setup interface application is executed.  If you are using GENPD.APP, the default printer setup interface application included with FoxPro, the Printer Setup Editing dialog appears so you can create a setup with the name you specified.  

When the printer driver setup name you include in <expC> does not exist in your resource file, you can prevent the printer driver setup application from executing by preceding the setup name with a dash (-).  When a dash is included before the setup name,  _PDPARMS is not cleared from memory. 

A default printer driver setup can be loaded when you start FoxPro by including the following line in your CONFIG.FP file. 

PDSETUP = '<setup name>'

Include the <setup name> to load when FoxPro is started.  Be sure to enclose the setup name in quotation marks. 



See also: _GENPD, _PDRIVER, SET PDSETUP, SET PRINTER 

",Sysmemvar pr nx
_PECODE,"
         _PECODE = <expC>        



Expression output when an ENDPRINTJOB command is encountered. 


<expC> may contain any collection of print codes up to a maximum of 255 characters; the default _PECODE is the null string.  Valid codes range from 0 to 255.

Consult your printer manual for complete information on the effects of specific control code sequences.



See Also:  ???, PRINTJOB ... ENDPRINTJOB, _PSCODE
 
",Sysmemvar pr
_PEJECT,"
         _PEJECT = <expC>        



Determines when FoxPro will send a page eject during output.


<expC>
	MUST be one of these:
		
		BEFORE	Page eject sent before starting output
	
		AFTER	Page eject sent after output is complete
	
		BOTH	Page eject sent before and after output
	
		NONE	No page eject sent before or after output

Only has effect within the PRINTJOB/ENDPRINTJOB command structure.



See Also:  EJECT, EJECT PAGE, _PADVANCE, _PECODE, PRINTJOB ... ENDPRINTJOB, _PSCODE 

",Sysmemvar pr
_PEPAGE,"
         _PEPAGE = <expN>        



Last page to be printed.


When _PAGENO reaches a value that's greater than the value stored in _PEPAGE, FoxPro halts the output of data.

_PEPAGE values may range from 1 to 32,767 (although the value of _PEPAGE can not be less the _PBPAGE).  The startup default is 32,767.  This system memory variable can be used in conjunction with _PBPAGE to print a range of pages.  If, for example, you wished to print only one page of a lengthy report, you could store that page number in _PBPAGE and _PEPAGE and only the one page would be printed.



See Also:  _PAGENO, _PBPAGE, PRINTJOB ... ENDPRINTJOB

",Sysmemvar pr
_PFORM,"
         _PFORM  = <expC>        



Print form file used with a print job.


The print form file (.PRF) contains a variety of print format settings, including the following system memory variables: _PADVANCE, _PAGENO, _PBPAGE, _PCOPIES, _PDRIVER, _PECODE, _PEJECT, _PEPAGE, _PLENGTH, _PLOFFSET, _PPITCH, _PQUALITY, _PSCODE, _PSPACING and _PWAIT.

If <expC> is a literal character string, it must be enclosed in quotation marks.

The print form file also contains the name of the destination file, if one was specified.

CREATE LABEL and CREATE REPORT store the system memory variable settings to a print form file when a report or label definition is created.  This form file is opened and loaded when the REPORT or LABEL is modified or printed.  However, the print form file settings are not automatically loaded when using the LABEL FORM or REPORT FORM commands.  To load the form file settings, you must specifically define the _PFORM system variable.



See Also:  CREATE LABEL, CREATE REPORT, MODIFY LABEL, MODIFY REPORT, LABEL, REPORT 

",Sysmemvar pr
_PLENGTH,"
        _PLENGTH = <expN>        



Number of output lines per page.


Used with _PLINENO to determine when a page eject is needed.

This value can range from 1 to 32,767.  The default is 66.



See Also:  EJECT, EJECT PAGE, ON PAGE, _PADVANCE, _PLINENO 

",Sysmemvar pr
_PLINENO,"
        _PLINENO = <expN>        



Current line number.


Establishes current line position and used to determine the next line for output.

As FoxPro sends output to the current print device, _PLINENO is incremented to indicate the current position.  This system memory variable may contain a value ranging from 0 to (_PLENGTH - 1).

Unlike the PROW() function which returns the current position of the printhead and is not incremented when SET PRINTER is OFF, _PLINENO is incremented whenever there is output (whether it's going to a printer, the screen or a file).  The SET PRINTER command has no effect on the _PLINENO value.



See Also:  _PCOLNO, PCOL(), _PLENGTH, PROW()

",Sysmemvar pr
_PLOFFSET,"
        _PLOFFSET = <expN>       



Left page offset.


Distance from the left edge of paper to the left edge of text in all printed output.  

Additional _LMARGIN space is calculated from the _PLOFFSET.  This system memory variable can contain a value from 0 to 254.  _PLOFFSET is equivalent to the SET MARGIN command.  Adjusting either one automatically changes the other.



See Also:  _LMARGIN, SET MARGIN

",Sysmemvar pr
_PPITCH,"
         _PPITCH = <expC>        



Current printer pitch.


<expC>
	MUST be one of these:
	
		PICA		10 characters per inch
	
		ELITE		12 characters per inch
	
		CONDENSED	about 17 characters per inch
	
		DEFAULT		current printer settings (default)

When you change _PPITCH to reflect one of the available values, the current printer driver will send an appropriate escape code sequence to the printer.  For _PPITCH values to have an effect, of course, the _PPITCH value must be supported by the present printer.  See _PDRIVER for information on setting printer drivers.



See Also:  ???, _PDRIVER, _PQUALITY

",Sysmemvar pr
_PQUALITY,"
        _PQUALITY = <expL>       



Print quality.


Determines whether output is printed using the current printer's letter-quality mode or default ""draft"" mode.

When _PQUALITY is set to true (.T.), FoxPro sends the necessary codes (based on the current printer driver) to produce higher quality printer output.

Generally speaking, when _PQUALITY = .F. the printer will print faster and when _PQUALITY = .T. it will slow down the output but produce better quality print. 


See Also:  _PDRIVER, _PPITCH

",Sysmemvar pr
_PRETEXT,"
        _PRETEXT = <expC>        



Expression output before a text line with SET TEXTMERGE.  


A tab or tabs may be stored to _PRETEXT to facilitate program indentation.



See Also:  SET TEXTMERGE, _TEXT

",Sysmemvar tm nx
_PSCODE,"
         _PSCODE = <expC>        



Expression output when a PRINTJOB command is encountered.


<expC> may contain any collection of print codes, up to 255 characters; with the default, _PSCODE, being the null string.  Valid codes fall in the range of 0 to 255.

Consult your printer manual for complete information on the effects of specific control code sequences.



See Also:  ???, _PECODE,  PRINTJOB ... ENDPRINTJOB

",Sysmemvar pr
_PSPACING,"
        _PSPACING = <expN>       



Printer spacing.


Determines whether FoxPro output will be sent with single, double, or triple-spacing.

The default is single-spacing (1).  <expN> must be a value from 1 to 3.  Values less than 1 or greater than 3 will generate an error.

The _PSPACING system memory variable can be set from within the Command window to alter output from commands such as DISPLAY or LIST.  It also controls how boxes will be drawn (a box defined with a height of 5, will be output with a height of 15 if _PSPACING is set to 3).



See Also:  ???, _PSCODE

",Sysmemvar pr
_PWAIT,"
         _PWAIT = <expL>         



Pause between pages of output.


This system memory variable is provided to allow printing on single sheets of paper, as opposed to continuous-feed (fan-fold) forms.  When a page is ejected from the printer with an EJECT command or when _PLINENO exceeds _PLENGTH, FoxPro suspends output to the printer so the user can manually insert another sheet of paper.



See Also:  EJECT, EJECT PAGE, _PLENGTH, _PLINENO 

",Sysmemvar pr
_RMARGIN,"
        _RMARGIN = <expN>        



Right margin position.


Position of the right margin (for output generated with the ? command).

The minimum valid _RMARGIN value is the greater of _LMARGIN + 1 or _LMARGIN + _INDENT + 1.  The maximum valid _RMARGIN value is 255.  The startup default is 80.  Only active when _WRAP is set to true (.T.).



See Also:  _INDENT, _LMARGIN, _PLOFFSET, SET MARGIN, _WRAP 

",Sysmemvar pr
_TABS,"
          _TABS = <expC>         



Location of tab stops in the printed output.


<expC> represents a tab list which is a series of comma-delimited numbers in ascending order.  By default, <expC> contains the null string which sets the _TABS spacing at eight character intervals (8,16,24,32,40,...).

If <expC> is a literal character string, it must be enclosed in quotation marks.

When _WRAP is set to true (.T.), any _TABS values greater than or equal to _RMARGIN are ignored.  The TABS parameter in the CONFIG.FP file is equivalent to _TABS, and specifying a TABS value automatically sets the value in _TABS.



See Also:  _INDENT, _WRAP

",Sysmemvar pr
_TALLY,"
         _TALLY = <expN>         



Number of records processed when a command is finished executing.


When the command is finished executing, the number of records processed is returned.  This number is stored to the _TALLY system memory variable.  Processing information is only directed to the screen or the current output window if TALK is SET ON.  

Commands that return information about their status include:

APPEND FROM	   INDEX		SORT
AVERAGE		   JOIN			SUM
CALCULATE	   PACK			TOTAL
COPY TO		   REINDEX		UPDATE
COUNT		   REPLACE
DELETE		   SELECT - SQL	

When you first start FoxPro, _TALLY is set to zero.  Executing one of the commands above replaces the previous _TALLY value with the result from the command.



See Also:  SET ODOMETER, SET TALK

",Sysmemvar db nx
_TEXT,"
          _TEXT = <expN>         



Redirect text merge output.


Directs output from the \, \\ and TEXT ... ENDTEXT text merge commands to a low-level file.

The \, \\ and TEXT...ENDTEXT commands facilitate the merging of text with the contents of database files, memory variables and the results of functions and expressions.  Output generated by these text merge commands can be directed to the screen or a window or to a low-level file.  The _TEXT system memory variable lets you direct text merge output to a low-level file.

Output from the \ and \\ and TEXT...ENDTEXT text merge commands can be sent to a low-level file by including the TO <file> clause in the SET TEXTMERGE command.  The file handle of the <file> specified in this clause is stored to _TEXT.  If the file handle of another low-level file was previously stored in _TEXT, that low-level file is closed. 

Low-level files may be created and opened with the FCREATE() file function, and existing files may be opened with the FOPEN() file function.  These functions return a positive file handle if the file is successfully created or opened.  Storing this file handle to _TEXT directs any subsequent output from the \, \\ and TEXT...ENDTEXT text merge commands to the file.  The STORE command or = operator may be used to store a file handle to _TEXT.  A low-level file opened to accept output from the text merge commands must be opened with write privileges.  

Low-level files can be closed with the FCLOSE() function or the CLOSE ALL command.  You may also use the command SET TEXTMERGE TO without a file name to close the low-level file whose handle is stored in _TEXT.

The startup default value of _TEXT is -1.  If text merge output is being directed to a file whose file handle is stored in _TEXT, the output to that file may be turned off without closing the file by storing -1 to _TEXT.  By storing different file handles and -1 to _TEXT you may direct text merge output to alternate files.  The following program exhibits how this may be done:  


         Program Example         


SET TALK OFF

SET TEXTMERGE ON NOSHOW	&& Enable text merge, no output to screen
SET TEXTMERGE DELIMITERS TO && Default text merge delimiters <<  >>

SET TEXTMERGE TO DATE.TXT && Create and send output to DATE.TXT
STORE _TEXT TO mdatehandl && Save DATE.TXT's file handle
STORE -1 TO _TEXT	&& Output off to DATE.TXT; keep it open

SET TEXTMERGE TO TIME.TXT && Create and send output to TIME.TXT 
STORE _TEXT TO mtimehandl && Save TIME.TXT's file handle

*** Send the following text to TIME.TXT ***

\The time is:

STORE mdatehandl TO _TEXT && Now direct output to DATE.TXT

*** Send the following text to DATE.TXT ***

\Today's date is:

STORE mtimehandl TO _TEXT && Now direct output to TIME.TXT

*** Output the time on the same line ***

\\ <<TIME()>>					

STORE mdatehandl TO _TEXT && Now direct output to DATE.TXT

*** Output the date on the same line ***

\\ <<DATE()>>					

CLOSE ALL		&& Close all files
TYPE DATE.TXT	&& See what's in this file
WAIT WINDOW		&& Pause
TYPE TIME.TXT	&& and what's in this file



See Also:  \ | \\, FCLOSE(), FCREATE(), FOPEN(), _PRETEXT, SET TEXTMERGE, SET TEXTMERGE DELIMITERS, TEXT ... ENDTEXT

",Sysmemvar tm nx
_THROTTLE,"
        _THROTTLE = <expN>       



Specify Trace window execution speed.


The Trace window, one of the many debugging tools available in FoxPro, displays a program's source code as the program executes.  Each line in the program is highlighted when the line executes.  

The numeric value of _THROTTLE determines the delay between execution of each program line when the Trace window is open.  The Trace Between Breaks option in the Trace window's Program menu must be on for a delay to occur between program line execution.  A diamond appears beside the Trace Between Breaks option when it is on.

The value of _THROTTLE is the delay in seconds between execution of each program line.  The start up default for _THROTTLE is 0 -- there is no pause between execution of program lines.  _THROTTLE can range between 0 and 5.5 seconds.  For example, if _THROTTLE is set to 0.5 seconds, a 1/2 second delay occurs between program line execution.  

The program execution delay can also be adjusted by selecting the Throttle... option from the Trace window's Program menu. 



See Also:  SET DEBUG, SET STEP 

",Sysmemvar pe er nx
_WRAP,"
          _WRAP = <expL>         



Enable or disable word wrap.


Determines whether automatic word wrapping of output will take place.

By default, _WRAP is set to false (.F.).

Whenever _WRAP is set to true (.T.), output from the ? command that would extend beyond the right margin (_RMARGIN) will automatically wrap to the left margin (_LMARGIN).   _WRAP must be set to true before _ALIGNMENT, _INDENT, _LMARGIN and _RMARGIN will have any effect on output.



See Also:  _ALIGNMENT, _INDENT, _LMARGIN, _PLOFFSET, _RMARGIN

