",Interface di
 Text Editing,"
          Text Editing           

This help topic briefly describes how to perform many text editing operations. 

Creating a New File
	Choose New... from the File menu popup.  A New File dialog appears.

Opening an Existing File
	Choose Open... from the File menu popup.  The Open File dialog appears.

Saving a New File
	Choose Save as... from the File menu popup.  The Save As dialog appears.

Saving an Existing File
	Choose Save from the File menu popup.


		Cursor Movement Keys
	Key				Cursor Action


Right Arrow			Moves one character to the right.

Left Arrow			Moves one character to the left.

Up Arrow			Moves up one line.

Down Arrow			Moves down one line.

PgUp				Moves up one window of text.

PgDn				Moves down one window of text.

Home				Moves to beginning of current line.

End					Moves to end of current line.

Ctrl+Right Arrow	Moves one word to the right.

Ctrl+Left Arrow		Moves one word to the left.

Ctrl+Home			Moves to beginning of text.

Ctrl+End			Moves to end of text.

Moving through text with a mouse
	Click on the arrow at either end of the scroll bar.  Drag the diamond-shaped thumb.  Point and click.

Entering Text
	Before you type text, position the cursor where you want the text to appear.  You don't have to press Enter every time the cursor reaches the right edge of the window.  You only need to press Enter to start a new paragraph.


	 Keys for Selecting Text

Shift+Arrow (Left/Right)
	Selects one character at a time.

Shift+Arrow (Up/Down)
	Selects one line at a time.

Shift+Ctrl+Arrow (Left/Right)
	Selects from cursor to beginning/end of word.

Shift+Ctrl+End
	Selects from cursor to end of text.

Shift+Ctrl+Home
	Selects from cursor to beginning of text.

Ctrl+A
	Selects all text.

To deselect text, press any cursor movement key.

Selecting text with mouse
	Position pointer on character where you want selection to begin, drag to the right by holding down the mouse button and moving the mouse, then release the mouse button.  Drag down to highlight entire lines of text.


Mouse Shortcuts for Selecting Text

Select a word
	Positioning pointer on the word and double-click. 

Select a line
	Position pointer on a line and triple-click.

Select text word-by-word
	Double-click and drag.
	
Select text line-by-line
	Triple-click and drag.

Select segment of text
	Position cursor then Shift+click at another location to select from the original cursor location to the Shift+click location.

Select all text
	Press Ctrl+A.
	

		Deleting Text

Backspace	If nothing is selected, deletes character to immediate left of cursor.  If text is selected, deletes selection.

Ctrl+Backspace	Deletes word in which cursor is positioned.  If cursor is positioned on blank space following word, space and previous word are deleted. 

Delete		If nothing is selected, deleted character that cursor is on.  If text is selected, deletes  selection.

Inserting Text
	Pressing the Insert key toggles between insert and overwrite mode.  The cursor looks like a flashing underscore when you are in insert mode.  Typing a character in insert mode inserts it at the cursor location to the right of existing text.

	In overwrite mode,  the cursor is a solid flashing box.  Each character you type replaces the character that the cursor is on. In general, when text is selected, typing any characters (except editor control characters) replaces the selected text with the typed text. 

Inserting Special Characters
	To insert a control character, press the ` key (left single quote) followed by the letter that would normally follow Ctrl.  For example, Ctrl+Q is inserted into a file by typing `Q.  To enter ` itself, you must type ` twice.

	High-bit characters used to create boxes and other graphics may be entered directly in editor files by holding down the Alt key and typing the (decimal) key code of the desired character.


	Cutting, Copying, Pasting

Text can be reorganized within windows and moved among windows using Cut, Copy and Paste from the Edit menu.

Cut		Removes selected text for placement in a different location.

Copy	Duplicates selected text for use in another location.

Paste	Places cut or copied text into a file at the cursor location.


           Undo and Redo          

Undo and Redo are available on the Edit menu popup.

Undo	Reverses most recent text editing action.  You can continue to Undo (in reverse order) all text editing actions that you've made since you opened the file or saved it during the editing session.

Redo	Reverses most recently undone command.


         Find and Replace         

When you want to find and/or replace a word or phrase that appears throughout a text file, program file, memo field or the Command window, choose the appropriate find and replace command from the Edit menu popup.  


    Setting Editor Preferences    

Preferences... on the Edit menu popup allows you to change certain settings that are in effect during editing sessions.  You can make the preferences apply to only the current file you are editing, or to all files of that type created in the future.



See Also:  Command, Find, Goto Line, New File, Open File, Preferences, Revert, Save As

",Interface di ge wi
 Title/Summary,"
         Title/Summary           

This dialog allows you to specify whether a title and/or summary band will be included in the report.  The Title/Summary dialog contains the following options:

[ ] Title Band
	Choose to include Title band in report.

[ ] New Page
	When checked, prints Title band on its own separate page(s).  Check New Page to issue a page eject after the Title band.

[ ] Summary Band
	Choose to include Summary band in report.

[ ] New Page
	Specify whether or not the Summary band is printed on its own separate page(s).  Check New Page to issue a page eject before the Summary band.



See Also:  Report Writer

",Interface di me
 Total,"
             Total               

Allows you to compute numeric field totals for records in active database.

This dialog contains these options:

Total on (List)
	Choose field to total on.
	
< Expr... > 
	Type in expression to total in text box or choose Expr... to display Expression Builder to create expression to total on.    When checked, and expression has been specified.

[ ] Scope...
	Brings forward scope dialog.  When checked, a scope other than ALL has been set.

[ ] For...
[ ] While...
	When checked, displays Expression Builder to specify For and/or While conditions.  When checked, a For and/or While condition has been set.

[ ] Fields...
	Displays Field Picker dialog.  When checked, fields have been specified.
	
< Save As... > 
	Enter name of destination database or choose Save As to display Save As dialog.

Choose OK push button to compute total.



See Also:  Expression Builder, Field Picker, Save As, Scope

",Interface di me
 Trace,"
              Trace              

The Trace window allows you to see your program as it runs.

Program Menu Popup
	Open...
		Displays Open File dialog to open a program.

	Cancel
		Ends execution of suspended program.

	Line Numbers
		Toggle option to display line numbers in a program. 

	Clear Breakpoints
		Removes breakpoints from program.

	Trace Between Breaks
		Toggle option to display and highlight every line of program code as it executes.

	Throttle...
		Displays Execution Throttle dialog to specify execution speed of programs.

Do.../Resume menu pad
	Displays Do dialog to open program. Program execution is suspended on first executable line.  Do... toggles to Resume after program chosen to continue program execution.  

Out menu pad
	Continues program execution to statement following line that called procedure currently executing.

Over menu pad
	Continues program execution, without displaying  executed lines of subprocedure, to next statement of same procedure.  

Step menu pad
	Continues program execution to next executable line and pauses.

You can pass parameters to a program or an application and then trace execution by following these steps:

	1.	Open the Trace window.

	2.	From the Program menu in the Trace window, choose Open... and choose the program or application.

	3.	Set a breakpoint on the first executable line of the program.

	4.	In the Command window, DO the program WITH the parameters.



See Also:  Command, Debug, Execution Throttle

",Interface me wi
 Try It,"
             Try It              

When a Menu Design window is active, you can check the results of your menu definition at any time by using the Try It push button.  When you choose the Try It push button, the menu system you've defined appears at the top of the screen and a Try It dialog appears that displays the file name of the menu system.  When you choose menu pads and submenu options, the prompt that was selected and the command that's assigned with the option are displayed in the dialog.



See Also:  Menu Builder

",Interface di
 Type,"
               Type              

The type dialog contains these options:


 Type 

	Choose an option to assign attributes and border to a window according to chosen option.  Choosing User enables all options in this dialog.

Attributes
	[ ] Close	When checked, allows user to close window from menu option, keyboard or with mouse.

	[ ] Float	When checked, allows user to move window to any position on the screen.

	[ ] Zoom	When checked, allows user to enlarge window to fill entire display area.

	[ ] Shadow	When checked, window is defined with a shadow.

	[ ] Minimize	When checked, window can be shrunk to a size of 1 row by 16 columns.

Border
	( ) None	Window has no border.

	() Single	Window has single line border.

	( ) Double	Window has double line border.

	( ) Panel	Window has a wide border (like system windows); defined controls are hidden.

	( ) System	Window has a wide border; any defined controls are visible.
	
Color Schemes
	
	 Primary  
	
	Allows you to specify a default color scheme for a window and the objects in the window except popups.

	
	 Popup  
	
	Allows you to specify a default color scheme for popups in the window.



See Also:  Screen Builder, Screen Layout

",Interface di
 Variable Definition,"
       Variable Definition       

In this dialog you can add new variables, change or delete existing variables, or change the order in which the variables are evaluated in a report.

This dialog contains these options:

Variable Name: 
	Enter name for variable.

< Value to Store... >

	Enter value in text box or choose Value to Store push button to bring forward Expression Builder.  

< Initial Value... >

	Enter initial value or choose Initial Value push button to bring forward Expression Builder.  Initial value is the value of the variable before any calculations are performed.

[X] Release After Report
	Check to release report variable from memory after report is printed.  If not checked, variable remains available in memory until you exit FoxPro or release the variable with the CLEAR ALL or CLEAR MEMORY commands.


 Reset 

	Allows you to specify point at which variable is reset to initial value.  By default End of Report is displayed on popup control, and End of Page is an option on the Reset popup.  

	If you have created groups in report, an option is displayed for each group in the report.

() None
( ) Count
( ) Sum
( ) Average
( ) Lowest
( ) Highest
( ) Std. Deviation
( ) Variance
	Choose a radio button to perform corresponding calculation on the variable.



See Also:  Expression Builder, Report Variables, Report Writer 

",Interface di
 View,"
              View               

The View window provides an easy way to open database files, establish relations and set many FoxPro switches.  Four push buttons display the different panels of the View window. 

< View >
	Displays View panel to control database files.

	< Setup >
		Displays Setup dialog.
	
	< Browse >
		Displays selected database in Browse window.

	< Open >
		Displays Open File dialog to select database to be opened in work area.

	< Close >
		Closes selected database and any associated files in current work area.

	Work Areas (List)
		Displays work areas and aliases for open databases.  Indexed databases are preceded by a ; databases with 1-to-many condition are followed by a .

	< Relations >
		Allows you to set relationship between databases.

	< 1-To-Many >
		Brings forward 1-to-Many dialog allowing you to set a 1-to-many relationship between databases.

	Relations area	
		Displays any relations that exist between database files in work areas.

< On/Off >
	Displays On/Off panel with 26 set controls for FoxPro.

< Files >
	Displays Files panel allowing you to set defaults for FoxPro.

	Default Drive popup
		Allows you to specify default drive for all file input and output operations.

	[ ] Path...
		Displays Select Directory dialog to specify path.  When checked, a path has been specified.  

	< Clear Path >
		Deactivates current path.

	[ ] Alternate...
		Displays Save As dialog appears to specify alternate file.  When checked, an alternate file has been specified.

	< Clear Alternate >
		Closes current alternate file.

	[ ] Procedure...
		Displays Open File dialog to specify procedure file.  When checked, a procedure file has been specified.

	< Clear Procedure >
		Closes procedure file.

	[ ] Help...
		Displays Open File dialog to specify a Help file.  When checked, a help file has been specified.
	
	[ ] Resource...
		Displays Open File dialog to Specify a resource file.  When checked, a resource file has been specified.

< Misc >
	Displays Misc panel allowing you to specify date, currency and time formats and make other FoxPro settings.

	
	 Date  
	
		Allows you to choose format for date expressions.

	[ ] Century
		When checked, displays complete four-digit year in all date output.

	[ ] Date Delimiter
		Allows you to specify date delimiter.  Type delimiter character of your choice in sample date.

	Decimals 
		Specify number of places to follow decimal point.

	Symbol 
		Allows you to specify string of characters to precede or follow currency value.

	[ ] Left
		Determines if symbol precedes or follows currency value.

	Sample number is displayed below currency settings to show how currency data will appear.  To change commas that appear in currency values, select delimiters in sample number and type different character, then press Enter.

	[ ] Clock
		Toggles clock on and off.  When checked, clock is on.

 	     
 	12 or 24
 	    
		Choose 12 or 24 hour format for clock.  

	Row			Column 
		Allows you to specify location of clock on monitor.  Coordinates can be adjusted (from 0 - 999).

	[ ] Bell
		Toggles bell on and off.  When checked, bell is on.
	
	Freq 	Length 
		Allows you to adjust error tone that computer emits.

	<>
		Sounds bell as defined with frequency and length.
	
	[ ] Talk
		Toggles SET TALK ON and OFF.  When checked, SET TALK is ON.
	
	Reporting Interval 
		Allows you to specify when information processed appears on screen when Talk is checked.

	Typeahead 
		Allows you to specify number of characters held in typeahead buffer.

	Mouse Tracking 
		Allows you to specify how sensitive pointer is to movements made with mouse.  



See Also:  1-To-Many, Browse, Expression Builder, Open File, Path, Save As, Setup

